All patients underwent chest CT using a multidetector scanner with the following parameters: display field of view (dFOV) 32 cm, 35 mA, 120 KV, 5 mm section thickness. All CT images were reconstructed with a section thickness of 1.25 mm and reviewed separately by two cardiothoracic radiologists (8 and 15 years of experience). Disagreements were resolved in consensus involving a cardiothoracic radiologist with 17 years of experience). All CT images were evaluated on lung and mediastinal windows for the following features: (1) presence of ground-glass opacity (GGO; Fig 2
), consolidation (Fig 3
); (2) presence of nodules or fibrosis; (3) number of lobes with GGO or consolidation; (4) site of the lesions: subpleural or not; (5) presence of the following signs: halo sign, reversed-halo sign, crazy-paving sign, sieve-hole sign, cavity sign, tree-in-bud sign; (6) presence of vascular dilatation, interlobular septal thickening, and bronchodilatation; (7) presence of pleural thickening, pleural effusion; and (8) presence of lymphadenectasis.
